@node Introduction 

    MoreTools is a simple utility able to add items  to the Workbench
  "Tools" menu to run programs or execute commands; you can also pass
  them a parameter by selecting some icons before or by using a file-
  requester.

    To use it all you need is WB 3.0+ and the asl.library.

@endnode


@node Usage

    MT can be started from shell ("run MoreTools >NIL:")  or from WB
  double-clicking on its icon or putting it in the WBStartup drawer;
  you can use command line  @{"parameters" link Configuration} or  @{"tooltypes" link Configuration} to modify its
  behavior (e.g. to change the default name of the @{"menu description" link Menu}
  "s:mtdata"). 

    If the menu description file  has a project  icon you can use it
  to start MT.
    
@endnode


@node Configuration "ToolTypes and Parameters"

   The template is "FILE/K,REQUESTER/S,MTCHANGE/s,MTQUIT/S"

   @{b}FILE <filename>@{ub}: (if used as tooltype: FILE=<filename>)
                    MT uses the specified file to build menu; the
                    default value is "s:mtdata".

   @{b}REQUESTER:@{ub}       MT asks for a filename when started.

   @{b}MTREQ:@{ub}           MT puts always "MoreTools" as last item.

   @{b}MTQUIT:@{ub}          MT puts always "quit MoreTools" as last item.

   
   note: MTREQ overrides MTQUIT (see @{" special keywords " link speckw}).

@endnode


@node Menu "Menu description"

    To build a menu MT needs a file with a menu description; you can
  write it with whatever text-editor. General rules to observe:

  - every line has to start with a keyword, other lines are skipped;
  - every line  can contain  only one keyword  (and, if required, an
    argument);
  - put a space between keyword and argument;
  - keywords can be written in upper- and lowercase;
  - the file has to be a simple ASCII file.

    There are @{"item description" link itemkw} and @{"special" link speckw} keywords;  for everyone
  of them the syntax (bold),  an example (italic) and a short remark
  (plain) are reported.

    You can also @{"pass a parameter" link passpar} to the program to run.
    
    In the MoreTools.lha archive you should find "MTData.example",an
  example of description file.  

@endnode


@node itemkw "Item description keywords"

    @{b}ITEM  <text>@{ub}
    @{i}ITEM     Show@{ui}
    <text> is the name of the menu item; every item description must
    start with this line;  the end is marked by another ITEM keyword
    or by a @{"special keyword" link speckw}.
    
    @{b}COMMAND <text>@{ub}
    @{i}COMMAND  Workbench:utilities/Multiview@{ui}
    <text> is the program to run with full path.

    @{b}OUTPUT <text>@{ub}
    <text> is the standard output for the program.
    @{b}OUTPUT DEFAULT@{ub} is a short form for
    @{i}OUTPUT  CON:0/40/640/150/MoreTools output window/auto/close/wait@{ui}


    Note: MT reads  the stack value  from the command's  icon (if it
          exists; default is 4096 bytes)

@endnode


@node speckw "Special keywords"

    @{b}MTQUIT@{ub}
    adds "quit MoreTools" like last item;  you can select it to quit
    the program.

    @{b}MTREQ@{ub}
    adds "MoreTools" like last item;  it permits to quit the program
    or to reconfigure  the menu selecting  the data file  (it  needs
    asl.library to work).

    If you use both MTQUIT is ignored.

@endnode


@node passpar "Passing parameters"

    To pass selected icon like a parameter you have to insert "%s" in
  the COMMAND line:

    ITEM     Show
    COMMAND  Workbench:utilities/Multiview %s

    So,  selecting  an icon  and then  the item "Show", MultiView is
  started and the object linked to the icon is loaded.

    Use "%d" or "%f" to use a filerequester to pass a directory or a
  file to the program to be executed:

    ITEM     Ed text
    COMMAND  Ed %f
    OUTPUT   DEFAULT

    It is possible use only one "%s" per line; there is no limit for
  "%f" and "%d".

@endnode


